<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="356" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,153,395]" pageId="5" pageNumber="356">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,261,287]" pageId="5" pageNumber="356">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is the Latin word 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wang &amp; Zhou" authorityYear="2020" box="[787,902,261,287]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Exomis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="5" pageNumber="356" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pubescens">
<emphasis box="[787,902,261,287]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="356">pubescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(pubescent) and refers to the setose body surface.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="356" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,153,395]" pageId="5" pageNumber="356">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,332,359]" pageId="5" pageNumber="356">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This new species differs from other congeneric species by the following characteristics: pronotum and elytra both pubescent; pronotum fulvous with a black rectangular spot at basal half.
</paragraph>
